# INTRODUCTION { #sec-intro }
On 27th January 2013, a fire at the nightclub Kiss caused the death of 
243 people in Santa Maria, Brazil. Investigators [@crea2013]
concluded that the fire was caused by use of flare stick which sparks
burned the flammable sound insulation foam (polyurethane made). 
In a few seconds, black and toxic smoke spread throughout the
nightclub, causing many people to faint. Others did strive towards 
the unique and undersized exit door. Kiss tragedy required improvements 
on fire safety code. As unit of Brazilian federation, each state, through
its fire department, is responsible to define the fire safety code and
assure its application. For example, one less than two years after Kiss, 
Santa Catarina Military Fire Department (CBMSC) launched its new fire safety code banning the use of any
type of fireworks and flammable foam in closed rooms. However, defining 
the size and number of emergency, being either safe and cost-effective is
not simple as setting another statement in a code. For this, an experiment was done
in order to analyze what happens during an uncoordinated egress like the one took place at Kiss. 
This paper presents results like exit blockages, crowd
turbulence and egress time and flow due to initial population. 

# UNCOORDINATED EGRESS { #sec-egress}

Based on literature review and empirical research, 
Helbing, Farkas and Vicsek [@helbing2000simulating] lists the events that can occur during
an emergency evacuation, right after the identification of the threat: 
(1) people try to move faster than normal; 
(2) individuals press to exit, causing physical interactions with those around; 
(3) movement becomes uncoordinated through the openings; 
(4) arcing and locks are observed; 
(5) jams form; 
(6) pressure become dangerous; 
(7) injured or fallen people act as obstacles; 
(8) tendency to mass behavior increases; 
(9) alternatives are neglected.

## Simulation
Helbing, Farkas and Vicsek [@ helbing2000simulating] brought with an egress
simulation model. In an emergency, every individual should aim the exit,
following a straight path in a desired speed. If those ahead are not at 
the same speed, they will be underwent by those behind, raising the crowd pressure.

Each individual is represented by a circle which diameter varies from
42.5cm to 52.5cm. The forces applied by and on objects are physical and
socio-psychological. The latter is related to people aversion people's 
cluster aversion to crowding. Physical forces are the reaction to
compression and friction, either among people or between individual and 
